    <h2>7.1 How Do Investors Evaluate a Company?</h2>
    <p>When investors buy stocks, the most important questions are:</p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Can this company make money consistently?</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Metrics: Gross margin, net margin, ROE.</li>
                <li>Investors want companies that not only make money but can maintain profits.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Does this company have a moat?</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Does it have advantages that are hard to imitate (brand, patents, network effects)?</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Can this company grow in the future?</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Is the industry trend upward (AI, electric vehicles, medical tech)?</li>
                <li>What position is the company in the industry?</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Is this company expensive now?</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Use valuation metrics (P/E, P/B, PEG, DCF) to judge if stock price is reasonable.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ol>
    
    <p>ðŸ‘‰ Conclusion: Investors pick companies not based on how hot they are today, but whether they <strong>can survive 10+ years</strong>.</p>
    
    <h2>7.2 How Can Entrepreneurs Build an "Investment-Worthy Company"?</h2>
    <p>If you're an entrepreneur, think in reverse: How to get investors to pick you?</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Gross Margin</strong>ï¼š
            <ul>
                <li>Startups should avoid "manual labor", preferably have high margins (like software, subscription models).</li>
                <li>Example: Adobe transitioned to subscription model â†’ gross margin 80%+.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Net Margin</strong>ï¼š
            <ul>
                <li>Can lose money early, but need clear path to profitability.</li>
                <li>Example: Amazon lost money in early years, but financial reports showed rapid revenue growth, investors believed it could make money in the future.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Moat</strong>ï¼š
            <ul>
                <li>Build unique advantages.</li>
                <li>Example: Tesla's moat is batteries + autonomous driving data; TSMC's moat is chip manufacturing process.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Growth Story</strong>ï¼š
            <ul>
                <li>Investors buy the future, not the present.</li>
                <li>Example: SoFi tells "financial supermarket" story, Meta tells "metaverse" story.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
